# Frontend Architecture Standard

## Purpose

This rule defines frontend architecture standards for the enterprise e-commerce platform.

Every frontend feature must be:

- Maintainable
- Accessible
- Performant
- Type-safe
- SEO-friendly
- Consistent with design system

This rule applies to all code under `apps/web/`.

---

# Scope

This rule covers:

- Next.js 14+ App Router
- React Server Components and Client Components
- shadcn/ui component library
- Tailwind CSS styling
- TypeScript strict mode
- Data fetching from FastAPI backend
- Server Actions and route handlers

It does not define:

- Backend API implementation (see `api/` rules)
- Database schema
- Infrastructure deployment
- E2E test configuration

Those topics have dedicated rules.

---

# Technology Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|------------|
| Framework | Next.js 14+ App Router |
| Language | TypeScript (strict) |
| Styling | Tailwind CSS |
| Components | shadcn/ui (Radix UI primitives) |
| Forms | React Hook Form + Zod |
| Client state | Zustand |
| Server state | React Server Components, fetch, cache |
| API consumer | Typed fetch clients against FastAPI REST |

Never introduce alternative UI libraries without an ADR.

---

# Architectural Principles

The frontend follows:

- Feature-first organization within `apps/web/src/`
- Server Components by default
- Client Components only when interactivity requires it
- Colocation of related files (component, test, styles)
- Composition over inheritance
- Explicit data boundaries between server and client

Dependencies flow:

```
Pages / Layouts (Server)
    ↓
Feature Components
    ↓
UI Primitives (shadcn)
    ↓
Domain Types (shared with API contracts)
```

---

# Project Structure

```
apps/web/
├── src/
│   ├── app/              # App Router pages, layouts, loading, error
│   ├── components/       # Shared UI and feature components
│   │   └── ui/           # shadcn/ui primitives (do not modify casually)
│   ├── features/         # Feature modules (catalog, cart, checkout, ...)
│   ├── lib/              # Utilities, API clients, constants
│   ├── hooks/            # Custom React hooks (client-only)
│   ├── store/            # Zustand stores (client-only)
│   └── types/            # Frontend-specific types; prefer generated API types
├── public/
└── next.config.ts
```

Organize by business capability inside `features/`, not by technical role alone.

Correct:

```
features/catalog/components/ProductCard.tsx
features/checkout/components/CheckoutForm.tsx
```

Incorrect:

```
components/all/ProductCard.tsx
components/all/CheckoutForm.tsx
```

---

# Server vs Client Components

Default to Server Components.

Use `"use client"` only when the component needs:

- Event handlers (onClick, onChange)
- Browser APIs (localStorage, window)
- React hooks (useState, useEffect, useReducer)
- Zustand or other client-only state
- Third-party libraries that require the DOM

Never mark entire page trees as client components. Push `"use client"` to the smallest leaf that needs interactivity.

Pattern:

```
ProductPage (Server) → fetches data
  └── AddToCartButton (Client) → handles click
```

---

# Data Fetching

Fetch from FastAPI in Server Components whenever possible.

Rules:

- Use typed API client functions from `lib/api/`
- Pass serializable props to Client Components
- Never expose secrets or service tokens to the client
- Use Next.js `fetch` caching and revalidation intentionally
- Handle loading and error states with `loading.tsx` and `error.tsx`

For mutations, prefer Server Actions when the flow stays on the server boundary. Use client-side fetch only for optimistic UI or real-time updates.

Never call FastAPI directly from Client Components with privileged credentials.

---

# shadcn/ui Usage

shadcn/ui components live in `components/ui/`.

Rules:

- Install components via the shadcn CLI; do not copy from random sources
- Extend via composition and variants, not by editing generated primitives unless fixing a bug
- Use `cn()` from `lib/utils` for conditional classes
- Follow Radix accessibility patterns built into primitives
- Match design tokens defined in Tailwind config

Custom components that wrap shadcn should live in `components/` or `features/*/components/`, not inside `components/ui/`.

---

# API Integration

The frontend consumes FastAPI REST endpoints.

Rules:

- Define request/response types aligned with OpenAPI spec
- Centralize base URL, headers, and error handling in `lib/api/client.ts`
- Map HTTP status codes to user-facing messages in one place
- Use Zod to validate external data at boundaries when types cannot be generated
- Never duplicate business rules that belong on the backend

See `api/00-api` and `api/01-rest` for contract details.

---

# Styling

Use Tailwind CSS utility classes.

Rules:

- Prefer design tokens (`text-muted-foreground`, `bg-primary`) over arbitrary values
- Mobile-first responsive breakpoints
- Dark mode via CSS variables if enabled in theme
- No inline styles except dynamic values that Tailwind cannot express
- No CSS Modules unless required for third-party integration

---

# Accessibility

Every interactive UI must:

- Be keyboard navigable
- Have visible focus states
- Use semantic HTML
- Provide ARIA labels where Radix does not cover them
- Meet WCAG 2.1 AA for customer-facing flows

Run axe or equivalent checks on checkout and auth flows before release.

---

# SEO

Customer-facing pages must:

- Export metadata via `generateMetadata` or static `metadata`
- Use semantic heading hierarchy
- Include canonical URLs
- Support structured data where applicable (see SEO skills)

Admin and account pages may use `noindex` when appropriate.

---

# Error Handling

Handle errors at three levels:

1. Route level — `error.tsx` with recovery action
2. Feature level — inline error states for partial failures
3. Global — `global-error.tsx` for catastrophic failures

Never swallow API errors silently. Log server-side; show safe messages client-side.

---

# Security

Frontend security requirements:

- Never store secrets in client code or environment variables prefixed without `NEXT_PUBLIC_` only when truly public
- Sanitize user-generated content before rendering
- Use CSRF-safe patterns for Server Actions
- Validate all form input with Zod before submission
- Do not trust client-side validation alone

Authentication tokens: prefer HTTP-only cookies set by the backend; avoid localStorage for session tokens.

---

# Testing

Required coverage areas:

- Unit tests for utilities and hooks
- Component tests for complex interactive UI
- E2E tests for checkout, auth, and cart (Playwright)

Colocate tests as `*.test.tsx` or in `__tests__/` next to source.

---

# Anti-Patterns

Never:

- Fetch sensitive data in Client Components with admin credentials
- Put business logic in UI components that belongs on the backend
- Create god components exceeding ~300 lines without splitting
- Use `useEffect` for data that Server Components can fetch
- Bypass the typed API client with raw fetch scattered across files
- Import server-only modules into client bundles
- Duplicate shadcn components with one-off copies

---

# Decision Rules

Before implementation ask:

Is this static or server-fetchable?

If yes → Server Component.

Does this need browser interactivity?

If yes → Client Component leaf.

Is this shared UI chrome?

If yes → `components/` or shadcn.

Is this feature-specific?

If yes → `features/<capability>/`.

Is this client-only ephemeral state?

If yes → Zustand (see `frontend/02-state`).

Is this form input validation?

If yes → Zod + React Hook Form (see `frontend/04-forms`).

---

# Validation Checklist

Before completing frontend work verify:

- Server Components used by default
- Client boundary is minimal
- shadcn/ui patterns followed
- API calls go through typed client
- Loading and error states exist
- TypeScript strict passes
- Accessibility basics covered
- No secrets in client bundle
- Feature files colocated correctly

